Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
Republican lawyers have only documented 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws from 2009 making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon has grown after the November 2010 elections, which saw 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in the year of 2011 alone.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce advance voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day and remove their right to vote from citizens with a judicial record.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana's law in 2008.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have been sponsoring bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such identification.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required ID card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than US$35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
Much more.
Students, voters considered to vote more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID cards issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use to vote the cards issued by these clubs.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
However, it appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers sponsored laws in 2011 abolishing voter registration on election day in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register approximately 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the enrolment rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the advance voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter accounted for only 13 percent of the state’s voters.
The same was true with Hispanics.
These accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In return, whites that made up 76% of voters accounted for only 46% of voters voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of Democratic governors.
The U.S. Advocate General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have enacted laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undeniably make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see it as a clear goal of influencing the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Centre shows that the states that passed these laws account for 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have significant impacts on the result of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Screening for prostate cancer: taking the test or not?
Indeed, the PSA test would sometimes present erroneous results, with false negative results or false positives, which lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
This is enough to make men already reluctant to take screening tests even more reluctant.
Take the test or not?
We have asked two experts for the opinion.
In studies in the United States, there was a lot of contamination between control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and have firm recommendations.
Another study, this one, which concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had screening and those who did not.
This study also demonstrated, with follow-up after 12 years, that we have between 30 and 40% more likely to have metastases if we are not screened.
So I recommend the test from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if you have a direct parent who has ever had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American origin are also more at risk.
The key is to make the right decision once you detect cancer.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
The patient must really understand the degree of risk of his cancer, by offering him the possible options, not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not affect life in the long term, and by opting, in these cases, for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who are detected of cancer will not be treated, because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
We'll suggest that they do active surveillance and if the disease progresses, we'll offer them treatment.
Increasingly, criteria for deciding who should or should not be treated are being determined accurately.
I would recommend taking the test.
But the important thing is to have a discussion with your doctor to determine whether or not we should pass it.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has created a tool to evaluate the pros and cons of the PSA test.
