The shelled Higgs boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is indeed believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be perfectly certain.
Let's still suppose that it is the Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem slim, and let's see what it is.
There is, in this world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot end up in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
However, even if particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the principle of exclusion of Pauli, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consistent roughly in some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In a corner is good citizens named fermions, who wisely obey the principle of Pauli.
And in the other are agitated the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - in any case, not for this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not address here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature spread and to which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, we must emphasize here, are not all creatures as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle having an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in this precise place, much like a pebble thrown in a pond.
From this "disturbance" an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very, very high energies, a little as if it were a frozen pond of which only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That is why it takes a huge particle accelerator like that of CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 27 km in circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
It is not all particles or materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a fridge.
And in the same way, it is not all particles that interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, hold) do not have one.
Now, what can "bring" all this research, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between observations and predictions of the MS.
They are also several to long for it to be found, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physique" and plug some holes of the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, proposing no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oops!).
But we haven't found such deviations at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of this research in the daily life of Monsieur and Madame Tout-le-Monde are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will not be.
Here: In the early 60’s, the pioneers of the laser, in Bell Laboratories, did not suspect the revolution that their work would trigger.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we have already told fire the physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 -, initially the laser was rather seen as a "lab gadget".
Imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although it was not at all its original intention, now serves as an "eye" for all the digital cameras in the world, and earned it the 2009 Physics Nobel.
This, of course, does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, you never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die... | Duty
With its Commission to die with dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate is to resume shortly as a bill prepares.
However, in this essential area, much remains to be done.
Le Devoir tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was eating him had left him a two-year respite.
"They had given me five years to live, I was seven years old," he said, half-fig half-grape, lying in bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care house in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for that,” he said.
The disease does its work: a huge weakness that prevents it from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, speaks to strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicine, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is that I'm being cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating," he said.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"During our life, we learn that a man, it pisses up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at home Victor-Gadbois.
Regressing to the child's stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“It depends on the person’s ability” to accept regression, he notes.
Because, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments are taking place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients entering the Victor-Gadbois hospice all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life prognosis of three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provides so-called "curative" care.
For 89-year-old A., the worst fear is to die "conscious and suffocated".
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good children,” she added.
“I don’t have any more wishes in life,” she says, before accepting that she is being put on a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting, in the coming days, for a last visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, we provide, with a group of volunteers, body care and food aid.
It is palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11 700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know that you all end up dying one day.
Here, life goes on in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the home’s doctors.
Whether in terms of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
At the dying, we will agree to provide mouth care with the brandy or the Pepsi, according to the request.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, died during the night.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help loved ones as much as patients,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the house Victor-Gadbois, the days follow each other but do not resemble each other.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who enjoys his last family assembly in the courtyard, well-wedded in his pillows while being toasted in his honor, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children, after trying everything to survive.
“For six months, there have always been three to five beds that are occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who are admitted to the house Victor-Gadbois arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal phase of his or her life, whether at home, in hospital or in nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Maison Victor-Gadbois and the Société de soins palliatifs à domicile du Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care offered to cancer patients.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec health care that raises fears among several doctors specializing in palliative care the adoption of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care luminaries including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, is circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not performing well enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before we agree to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without being done to relieve her.
I'm afraid that patients will only ask to die because they don't receive adequate care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are relentless on their patients until the last day, despite the worst predictions.
Hélène Richard's survival expectations were already minimal when she gave up hard-working chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
Still, she told me I was finished!
Not all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not having granted their request after they have been relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Société de soins palliatifs à domicile du Grand Montréal, patients are resistant to pain treatment in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which amounts to sleeping the patient until the time of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of the suffering.
More and more, the unrelieved patient will have the possibility to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same phrase: "I want to die. "
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
