A Constitution at the Force in Egypt
This is a new poker shot from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants him full powers, he has decided to play his all-out.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given this House two more months to finish its work.
Egypt has almost been relying on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the divide in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "betray his word" and "trample on the law".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to put an end to the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within two weeks.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to renounce their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while protest is raging throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote favorably, as he claimed in an interview with the US weekly Time.
Especially since this recourse to a hasty vote is due to the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I keep the full powers", these supposedly to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were missing.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, believing that they had not been able to make their opinions.
The same had been done by representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacement members, were added in a hurry, yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, it was most often unanimously that the articles were voted on.
Commentators have also had fun with the fact that one of the only differences of the day has been expressed around... the time of prayer, some members of the committee believing that the clock of the constituent was poorly settled.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
Objects of all attention, Article 2 finally remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law."
The Salafi parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to be able to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have allowed for stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," the Liberals respond, who only see a communication coup.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They relate in particular to Article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The Liberals' fears are further fueled by the fact that the next president of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema but academics, for some trained in the French system," tempers Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic case law, ed.].
And the question in the future could arise as to what extent civilian judges are competent to rule on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another contentious point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the Defence Budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will the trial of civilians be banned in military courts, as requested by human rights associations.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and the insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially of the press.
In addition, no article echoes the protection of women, says Heba Morayef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy sites, the Center of the World and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and a wilderness.
Argoumenty i Fakty has retained five great reasons to visit Israel.
Go and love the holy places
Unavoidable rendezvous: the banks of the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who penetrates these "baptismal backgrounds" will be touched by the divine Grace.
As for the Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he soothed the storm or where the fishing was miraculous.
It was at this very place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
Believers travel the Rue de la Suffrance or the Way of the Cross (in Latin: the Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the courtroom), where the trial was held, then led by the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Anointing and the burial.
This is where the Christian center of the world is located, symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the Monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wailing Wall that constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC. J-C.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave small words accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel high
Visit the ruins of the Massada fortress, an ancient refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC. J-C. for his family.
These ruins are found on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can go there on their own.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1 600 and 2 040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs want pagan gods to once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting that are really worth a visit.
First: the Israel Museum near the Knesset (the parliament).
It houses the very ancient manuscripts of Qumran, or Dead Sea Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
Also worth seeing is the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
We mainly exhibit the paintings of the Impressionists and the expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of casts from visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin's sculptures.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The Fifth Museum is the Yad Vashem Holocaust Museum or Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars are sparkling.
You hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel's three major resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, because the temperature of the water does not drop below 21 ° while that of the air can reach 23 °.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point of the Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure-colored water contains brine and retains the bathers very easily, even those who do not know how to swim.
The surrounding landscapes are of surreal beauty.
We come to carry out a treatment based on salt water, silt, healing muds and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in the ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived here a long and happy life.
Tourists especially like to walk through the narrow alleys that bear the name of the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you touch the street walls corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come to do photo shoots from all over Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk in the Roman theater, "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of the Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera shows.
Note to tourists
If you are leaving for Israel, do not worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to the euro, because they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, these are mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only subway line in the country, consisting of six stations and capable of connecting the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The journey through all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition is to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday night to sunset on Saturdays, markets, shops and public transport cease their activity.
And the work week begins on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish dough, different sauces, balls of ground chickpeas, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk around the haughty air.
You can see them sleeping on the rooftops of parked cars.
These felines love passing places and do not refuse to be feasted.
The rental of a car varies according to the brand from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
An entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The language of numbers
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mainly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists went to the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Who language has, in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists are controversial about what the mandatory language testing law will give, fraudsters selling "false" certificates have already appeared in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are Central Asian nationals: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families staying at home.
Since 1st December, a law has entered into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian examination.
At this time, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sector.
However, over time, promises the Federal Migration Service, the tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the history of Russia and the foundations of law.
It will be necessary to validate his language skills in Russian to obtain and renew his work permit.
Nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt only.
Persons who have obtained teaching certificates or diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centers will be under the aegis of the Russian Language Institute Pushkin, the University of Peoples' Friendship, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions in Russia.
Immigrants will be able to take the exams in all the cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce reviews was supported by the State Duma's deputies and the Federal Migration Service.
But, before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will that give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, respond the representatives of the migration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery at work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, says the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for migrants without profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without the understanding of the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "trip" to an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will torment themselves for months without food and paperless and will have to work between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"At home, we promise them one thing, and when they arrive, we cheat them, we take their passport, and they do not receive the expected salary," confirms the Head of the Directorate of Migration Services for the work of the migration service of Tajikistan, Tolib Charipov.
Don't argue with me, Mr. Policeman!
However, many nationals of the Central Asian republics who wish to come and make money in Russia say that they do not only know the language of the country they wish to travel to, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow even a fair primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children without talking about dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people go to earn money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It’s hard when you don’t know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
Human rights defenders, however, note an important aspect of the language law.
The examinations will be intended only for migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no examination or official work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or defense to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 ruble miles.
And then, one can get a false recording quickly for only 1 500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we have no recording, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask us for 100, 200 rubles, something to buy cigarettes, tea," Umed Khushkadamov, a Tajikistan national, told reporters.
"Be quick, don't skimp and buy yourself a beautiful work of art"
From the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that the registration documents of migrants were not the only ones to be false.
Several false language examination certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
The falsified papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to make the task of the examinations easier had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Power representatives and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "pieces of paper".
The authorities can give to migrant workers who have not been able to validate the exam the first time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not handle the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very small
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against civilian gunholders.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it is the shootings made during the weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who left seven dead.
Police want to ban the carrying of rubber guns in public places and raise the legal age of obtaining a gun licence by increasing it from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Security and Anti-Corruption Committee, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that the amendments to the Weapons Act would be introduced in the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "squeezing the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are certain that the strengthening of civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, we can find today in Moscow any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior says it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black market of weapons is supplied via several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served ten years in the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot from a site taking arms orders
The first is "the military trace", that is, the weapons that were stolen during the military operations in the Caucasus.
“These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by the Caucasians,” Baranets said.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both the weapons stolen from the police stockpiles and those stolen directly from the law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of these have often been blown up.
“Attested versions indicate that some fires were deliberately started to conceal the deficit,” the former soldier said.
For Baranets, the weapons manufacturers are for something.
"We see private weapons factories that do not compete with competition in the international market and flow weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow," said an expert.
One of the other sources of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyz.
"There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," adds the former soldier.
Where did the guns come from?
The experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the subject was compiled in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Specialists analysed the reports of the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from the weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, comes from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market found themselves there "because of the fault of employees whose work is related to weapons", the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from the scene of military conflicts, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from "smuggled eddies".
A salesman and consultant of an armory who has asked to remain anonymous assures that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these specialists of the clandestine search; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, the sellers go to look for the new goods in military warehouses.
The person purchases a unit through a sign, such as a TT gun.
We give it to him by passing the goods through a fence.
"He transports her to the city and sells it for €900 per unit with two chargers," he says.
“It is true that the police are aware of all cases, so when crimes are about to be solved, they make a purchase of control from illegal arms dealers,” the seller added.
" Like in a luxury shop "
The seller and the buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I consulted sites, blogs, until a guy came forward and offered to come to Begovaya station where someone was getting me to a "corner" to bargain.
The price of the gun, I was given it on the spot
Victor Baranets as Military Observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the seller. I know someone, but I don't trust them.
There are sellers on the markets, but there you have to come too saying for example "On the part of such a person, who asked me to transmit that his daughter has lost a tooth".
Now I even buy a pair of American fists using someone I trust.
He only gives them to me because he knows I won't give it away.
Newcomers look for weapons in different ways.
Former military officer Victor Baranets tried himself as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990's when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The schemes, he said, have not changed.
We gave him a photo album in which there was "everything we want".
“I thought I was in a luxury boutique,” the soldier recalls.
There is no secret to the buyer, says Baranets, we can try everything.
As a potential customer, I don't just buy, we go with the seller in the forest and we set up a target.
