Already under the previous regulation, the provider (e.g. the Regional Council, in the case of regional operational programmes) forced the controlled subjects to accept that any breach of the market law signified a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it really helpful to make the law tougher in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or abuse the system but not punish those who make formal errors without consequence on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
What is the solution to get out of it?
Let's look where we're not going.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the SDO would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called Švarc system - what does that mean?
Is the Švarc system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be enforced in one way or another, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent the action of an authority responsible for going to inspect and require compliance with the law.
He can say, “We’re going to change the law and allow it,” but he can’t say we’re going to act like nothing has happened.
The Markets Act contains relatively strict rules on the formalities to be completed, precisely in order to protect the tender.
But it is also tragic that a tenderer should be eliminated solely because of formal defects.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and that is, in my opinion, what is lacking in us.
The roads are frozen in frozen places, but most remain passable.
In some parts of the Czech Republic, the roads are frozen and also snowy.
However, the network remains largely passable, in some places with increased vigilance.
Karlovy Vary Region
In the area of Karlovy Vary, the roads were passable this morning, but in frozen and also snowy places.
Temperatures have dropped and oscillate between -5 ° and -10 ° C but they should rise slightly in the day.
The snowfall has ceased in the region and only a thin layer of snow remains in the plains.
The ridges of the Metal Mountains (Krušné hory) are however covered with about 30 centimeters of snow.
Data from the Regional Road Maintenance Service indicated that due to fog, visibility was reduced in places.
The R6 expressway and the region's national roads are now without difficulty.
However, vigilance remains to be placed, for example on certain bridges whose coating can be frozen and slippery.
All departmental roads and third category lanes, including mountain roads, are also passable.
There are still on some of their stretches of frozen snow and in places compacted by traffic.
Especially in the areas located at altitude, drivers must increase their vigilance.
Regions of Pardubice and Hradec Králove
The Roads and Highways Directorate reports on its website that some roads in East Bohemia are threatened by the formation of ice and that traffic-packed layers of snow may be found on roads in mountainous areas and located at altitude.
