Šimon Ornest said: "In concert, we want to collect positive energy. "
What do you think of the fact that in less than a month it should be the end of the world?
It's just one of those alarming news stories, the kind of traps we like to fall into.
In our group The Tap Tap, we laugh rather and we think that we are the only group able to collect a positive energy remnant in order to push back or prevent the end of the world.
In addition, you are putting together in December a very unique project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you present this project to our readers in more detail?
This is a charitable action that we have been preparing for two years.
We decided to use the potential marketing of the end of the Mayan calendar announced for December 21 at 11 a.m.
The day before, on 20 December, three concerts will take place simultaneously, in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end practically when the Mayan calendar on the island of Kiribati that is in the Pacific Ocean ends, on a time zone up 12 hours from us.
Who had this idea?
At first I think it was my idea, then we designed everything with our creator, Honza Augusta.
Apart from the fact that we want to collect enough positive energy to save the world, we also want together, with the public, to reflect on the state of the world we leave to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have created a collection of unique items, including shoes, T-shirts, bags, and original keys against the end of the world, buying them online at www.e-tap.cz people can also support us.
The band The Tap Tap with other performers also recorded a hymn against the end of the world called "End of the World Cancelled" (in Czech "Konec světa zrušeno").
It is already very popular on YouTube, will we also hear it during these charity concerts?
Of course, at the very end, finally, if we succeed and the end of the world does not take place...
It will be sung simultaneously by all the performers in all three concerts.
The anthems will also meet at some point as part of a live, quite unique, show of Czech television.
The lyrics of this song were written by Tomáš Hanák who also plays the main role of Jesus in the music video, Xindl X also sings...
How did you come to cooperate with them?
We collaborate with other personalities of the Czech show-biz, due to the fact that we organize many concerts and charity events...
We strive to involve them intensively in these projects.
It turned out that most of them are interested in such cooperation and that it amuses them.
What will the benefits of these concerts against the end of the world be used for?
To equip the Studeo training center which is accessible to people with reduced mobility and which we work to carry out within the framework of the Jedlička Institute, with the Tap association, and this for six years.
Teachers regularly visit the students of the Jedličkův Institute and offer them activities that interest and entertain them.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to classes, we try to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the construction of the Jedlička Institute, we will transfer this project to a new independent building.
Several music groups and performers will take to the stage during each of these concerts?
By what criteria do you choose them?
We have tried to develop a program that is aimed at all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will be on stage.
You can find all the details on www.kpks.cz.
Are you also preparing for other "mega events" of this kind in the future?
In May, we will play for the first time as part of the Prague Spring; there too, we will surely prepare a quality program with interesting guests.
We would also like to play next year in the House of the Czech Republic in New York and personally, once there in the United States, I would like to combine concerts in Washington and Chicago.
Your international projects are minimalist, so far you have played for example in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is nevertheless a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage the organization and logistics of your tours?
It's not that bad that it looks at first.
We have five members in electric chairs whose machines have to travel in the hold, of course we also carry a lot of luggage and instrument boxes....
So far everything has gone more or less always well, ČSA and British Airways were always perfectly prepared for us, they surprised me more than once.
Even in Moscow, where we came back from recently, everything went without problems.
Thanks to your travels abroad, you can compare how these countries differ in terms of access facilities for people with reduced mobility, the attitude of public opinion towards people with disabilities and so on.
What have been your experiences so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than at home, we have justly witnessed in Moscow that in the east all is still in an initial phase.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is still very little accessible to people with disabilities; there, it is not yet common for a person to move alone in an electric chair in the center of the city.
They do not yet consider it obvious to give priority to a person in a wheelchair in an elevator.
Fortunately, there too, an association trying to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities is being created.
How do we still have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are many things we are still late for...
It is important to mention that improvements and developments are always dependent on the efforts of those involved.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with a severe disability to move alone in public spaces; they can go to the toilet, the museum, anywhere...
It is still not very common there that a large number of people with disabilities actively participate in social life, on this point, you, The Tap Tap, are rather on the contrary at the forefront of progress!
Public respect and access facilities are one thing, but the situation will really start to change when we have famous athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers.
For the moment, these are only isolated cases of people who have a strong will.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, let's go back a few years, what prompted you in 1998 to create this band?
I started working as an educator at the Jedlička Institute, where I found myself surrounded by many young people willing to invest in something.
And since I am a musician myself (I play, among other things, saxophone), with a colleague, we created a music activity.
And then, over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, we lost a little control of the situation (laughs).
Success has only happened in recent years, if I'm not mistaken?
That's right, creating connections with well-known singers and actively working to promote the band helped us.
We understood that if a job is not visible, it is as if it does not exist in the background.
Thanks to the subsidies of the European Union, we can also allow ourselves to have quality teachers, equipment, and so on.
Did you aim to reach such a level with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt that there was potential to change things.
Show business is full of stuff that copies each other.
In a way, it makes sense: everything new is accepted with caution and it lasts a long time.
Few are the original projects, and I dare to say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us for the first time is naturally pity, it is natural...
But pity is totally useless, because people with disabilities are not suffering beings, abandoned by all, whom we must take pity on.
They are people who can live a life in their own right and flourish, provided they have the necessary means of course.
I often say that when people with disabilities manage to achieve something, it is not only a step forward for them but for the whole society.
Isn’t your success also due to the fact that you are a demanding leader, as you are qualified by many people?
If we want to do quality work, we must be uncompromising in many areas and require some discipline.
But I think it's perfectly normal.
Some people come to our house with a romantic vision and head in the clouds and, when they realize that they have to come to rehearsals twice a week, take the preparatory classes and spend a lot of time on the roads for the concerts, they quickly lose their enthusiasm.
But it works the same in every group that wants to work and achieve goals.
The Tap Tap Group currently has twenty members.
How many of them were already there in 1998?
Only one, Láďa Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come in and go, we can't help it.
Our doors are always open to those who want or would like to join us.
This will be the case the day before the planned day of the end of the world, Thursday, December 20, 2012 from 9 p.m.
