Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as a twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started a close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the years that followed participated in a number of the Agency's projects.
However, the road from Poland to space began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on spaceflight; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
The said Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote numerous books on this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a propagator of world-renowned astronautics, his contribution was rewarded in particular by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the far side of the Moon.
In 1925, a draisine was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, we do not know the author or the details of this project.
It is also unclear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the draisine.
The only known information about this draisine is that of the press of the time.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
The documents retained show that this research had reached the stage of testing.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric fighter rocket, drawn by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects had the purpose of military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all plans to use the rocket technique were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee had been created in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish astronautic society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is talk of a company in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problem, in which are found four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics
By this time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research was looking future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and by the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He retained his office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, RM-1A was built and, in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were initiated in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been capable of carrying out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965, succeeded the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C by 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of machinery was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision has raised a strong discussion in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to examine this issue from a broader point of view.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means concretely that the different economic entities as well as the national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of freedom of trade and the (limitless) free movement of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in the price of labour (salaries) generate a strain on prices.
The following meaning should be put to this end: a producer shall strive by importing goods sold low-on-take to resist economic competition by "making the competitor's price more expensive", with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thus increasing its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transfer production abroad, or buy at low prices, or disappear. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the State's social charges necessarily increase.
All this situation intensifies the perfect bad will of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole of society by this race for profit.
This situation is so publicly aware that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital generate in the various economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to their homes.
In other words, governments are putting their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking into account social collapse.
This is mainly reflected in the amendments to the laws in force.
The objective is to force economically its own population to accept the dictates of the prices of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This is done on the one hand by a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and on the other hand by restricting the rights of employees in the field of labour legislation.
The result is increasing poverty and deepening the differences between the rich and the poor.
In the FRA, there have been public food distribution points for the poor for years who cannot support themselves with their own work.
There are already millions of these people.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay extra to reach the subsistence minimum.
For example, such a scandal has been uncovered in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all the southern Member States of the EU undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century) or to live with wages of misery, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital will invest in their country.
The question is: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to all of Latin America.
The liberal theory and the media claim, on getting tired of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the directed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence and, even, does not direct today, according to its own selfish interests, politics and by the same, the entire state.
The answer to this question is definitely yes.
The proof of this is that there is a lobby that is virtually all-powerful and present in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the field of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the FRG, the situation is such that, due to the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the development of bills to law firms closely related to industry.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
The totality of power does not come from the people, as the Western-style constitutions declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberalism-oriented democracies are now rapidly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The state had long been in full decay and the functions were attributed by violence.
Bribery, illegal favors, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The under-tables and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with votes already sold. ... "Honest people did not seek office at all, it resulted once the state stayed 8 months without consuls." “We were really beginning to say that the remedy for this difficult situation was an autocracy and that we had to choose an energetic man.” It is true that Appianos had Pompey in mind, but it was Caesar who irreversibly turned democracy into an absolutist regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, today's society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard to the interest of society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and assert the interests of society as a whole.
The result is, today as it was in the past, a decadence without precedent of the elites, without any effort to carry out far-reaching reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
As things stand, the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal democracies can be considered a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises that we are witnessing today, and the crimes against humanity as we know them through ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both at international and internal European level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution is socio-political reforms, which will strengthen state capital investment in the economy, increase citizens' influence on government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
