The movie Argo: When everything goes to the worst, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters made up of Islamist students stormed the U.S. embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, indeed, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, a blow further aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempt to release the hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following the negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate in the United States sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment.
The Iranian debacle contributed heavily to Jimmy Carter’s defeat to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered America a small victory.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated adventures, they found themselves in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In collaboration with Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran with an incredible cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who came to make scouting for the shooting of a film with a great science fiction show.
Combination of genders
Exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan requires Hollywood collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of many genres.
It is on the one hand a political thriller designed in a realistic way but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful blow, of a treachery - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen.
The atmospheres follow one another: sequences of Tehran of documentary style (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and the way in which, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no big differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
From a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting stopped arousing ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film that doesn't take place in his hometown of Boston.
The sense of atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his first films above the Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where Tehran's role "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity which also suggests confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake film crew in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to settle for a subject offering in fact few thrilling scenes, in the cinematic sense of the word.
It does very well, it sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the airstrip is quite far-fetched).
Argo's weakness lies in its dispelled character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood cooperators, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a little dramatic tension, he lets himself be seen with moderate interest, enjoying the realization and retro style of the 70's.
It trains the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story still, in a way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the trick.
Rules to inflate balloons, bananas and circus
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conducts an annual public inquiry into the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to launch the contest of the rules or ideas from the most absurd "EU workshop".
"The fact that the EU is planning, in recent times, to adopt a quota of 40 percent of women for the management of the big European companies has been at the origin of our decision," said Patrik Nacher, organizer of this survey.
Among the nonsense mentioned is, for example, the recent decision of the European Court to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, however, women were advantaged in terms of life insurance rates because they represent, objectively, a lower risk for insurance companies.
People can point out until the end of the year any other such incredible idea of the "EU workshop".
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013," Nacher said.
Among the controversial EU regulations is, for example, the obligation to add organic components to fuels, which has harmful consequences for the environment, or the prohibition on the use of reliable mercury thermometers, only because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance or the directive on the size of cages of chickens, which has led to the increase in the price of eggs.
Criticisms have also been made in the past against the de facto ban on the use of the phrase "butter spread" or the withdrawal of the sale of conventional light bulbs.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters in size.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or a group of states (for example the Czech Republic is currently imposing the demands of its banks by threatening to use its veto power).
The interests of the pressure groups are also, for example, at the origin of the fact that in the Union, bananas must not be of a size of less than 14 cm or have an "abnormal curvature".
The European Commission has defended itself by arguing that it is only harmonising non-homogeneous national standards that complicate trade.
The standards for fruit and vegetables have been relaxed despite opposition from some states, claiming that existing guidelines lead to food waste.
The first prize may be awarded in this survey to last year's EU regulation that a warning must be on inflatable balloons indicating that children under 8 years of age should not inflate without adult supervision.
The EU has referred to a US investigation that balloons are, among toys, the leading cause of child death by suffocation.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 when it comes to blowing in fair trumpets.
We have strange ideas in our house, too.
The following rule concerning European officials themselves is quite absurd: because of the sensitivity of this theme for Greece, anyone with an official function in the EU cannot use the name "Macedonia" and must, instead, speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the association "Laissez Faire" bringing together liberal economists, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com has appointed in this survey, in addition to some of the above mentioned absurdities, the Union regulation concerning the volume of food reserves in the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for food reserves that could be found in the territory of the Czech Republic on the day we joined the EU.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the volumes fixed for canned mushrooms and therefore faced a heavy fine.
The organizers of this survey considered interesting the idea of paying money to certain countries because they do not have access to the sea and the idea of granting a subsidy to apply for the granting of subsidies.
However, these ideas are not from Brussels but from Prague.
"The fact of not having a sea handicaps us.
We will ask the European Union for a refund." In the autumn of 2004, the Minister of Agriculture at the time Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) spoke.
He argued that, because of our wheat production, and as a result of the so-called "interventionist" purchases, the state had found itself with full stocks that it had then had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us millions of euros, because the Czech Republic is far from the ports.
Ultimately, the European Commission responded positively to Czech demand and organised a call for tenders for the purchase of wheat from countries without maritime access.
Grants for grants were proposed to municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), which were intended, in practice, to write applications for grants granted by Brussels.
The EU says: "Weird regulations are rare."
While regulations often give rise to criticism in the Member States, according to many experts, the EU's efforts to regulate and improve the effectiveness of the functioning of the Union and its overall development deserve praise.
More serious is, for example, according to experts, the problem of the use of EU subsidies for projects that have absolutely nothing to do with strengthening European integration, but which were imposed by Member States during the budget negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other EU countries, must fight in Brussels for the right to use specific denominations for these traditional products (a struggle from which it does not always emerge victorious) arouses strong emotions among the Czechs.
If at the end of six years of battle against the Germans and Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the name "Olomucké tvarůžky", for the name "Tuzemský rum" which dates back to us in the nineteenth century, our producers had to replace it with the name "Tuzemák".
Only products based on cane sugar alcohol, and not beet sugar, may bear the name of rum.
In the official list of registered products of the EU, today is found in the company of world-famous cheeses such as Feta or Gorgonzola, the massepain of Lübeck or of the parma ham, the biscuits of Karlovy Vary ("Karlovarské suchary"), the carp of Pohořelice and Třeboň ("Pohořelický a Třchmel").
Pardubice's gingerbread ("Pardubický perník") and cakes called "Hořice's Horns" ("hořické trubičky") can also be proud of their community brand.
People want me to save the Republic, but I'm just an amateur, says Senator Okamura
Senator, how do we get the idea of running in the presidential election?
It is not to be a senator or president who matters to me.
If everything worked smoothly in our country, I wouldn't be a candidate anywhere.
But I can no longer stand to see how the country has been looted for the last twenty years, that thieves are not locked up and taxes and the age of retirement are increasing.
I didn't have the ambition to become a politician.
But when I see something that I don't like, then I try to bring a solution to make it change.
And since I am over forty years old and I am an independent member of any party, I have no other solution to influence the situation than to stand in the presidential or Senate elections.
You entered the Senate but quickly set out for the Castle (N.d.T.: seat of the presidency).
Do you not turn your back on those who elected you?
I have always said that I will engage in the battle for the Castle according to the results of the Senate elections
Subsequently, I made it clear that if I were elected a senator, I would run in the presidential election.
My goal is not the function, it is only an instrument allowing me to realize my vision.
That is why I need the greatest influence and the broadest mandate.
