The architects of the firm MVRDV prove that the real adventures are not only about imagination. To be convinced, it is enough to contemplate Spijkenisse and the mountain of newly erected books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large company nearby, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed beautiful, this building".
I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has internet, iPad and e-books.
Today, no one goes voluntarily to one of these cheesy libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory city that is not attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a fairly special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give some neurons back to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get their hands on the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam MVRDV architectural firm, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of spirited and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and presented himself to the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a sneer on his face.
And while the members of the jury still looked at each other, bewildered and shrugging their shoulders, Maas, the brazen, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make a pyramid, and finished his speech supported by activist arguments by a "dear common!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain has sprang from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and some terraced buildings and houses for a total of 50 dwellings.
In early November, the mountain of books was awarded the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
The project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this small dull village, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of a mind-boggling ugline, whose white facades invite us to think that they house a dairy, has been enriched with a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Certainly, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open to you when you tread the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant streetlights unequivocally speak the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for the eyes of public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, the library shelves are along the facade and in the middle is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Willy Maas.
We completely disrupted the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been skillfully arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical power plant of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes panelling, sometimes railings, sometimes stair railings.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and building engineers do not want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
Thus, one day we found in a Frisian agricultural company an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membranes have been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we save time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, and then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane has been compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and transforms into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and pot ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they contribute above all to maintaining the ideal level of humidity of the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the new soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only lights up the inside, even on sunny days.
The thick wooden beams mounted across the glass facade serve as a sun visor, intercepting much of the spokes.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "finally found soul".
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the voids of the library which was not yet fully stocked (today, it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing on all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe that our invitation created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has reached the main discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Even though she may seem young and poorly educated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany chose abstention in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the US and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request to obtain observer state status with the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must exercise caution, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think she doesn't support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but did not be too critical of Israel.
During the insurgency in Libya in March 2011, Germany also chose abstention in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany having difficulty in taking a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy, so to speak, defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union makes the situation difficult.
The Germans therefore face several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe they are still groping to find this role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, such as in France or Great Britain
What does the term “normal” foreign policy mean specifically for the Germans?
It shows the desire to adopt positions beyond those of the United States and European partners, including national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of the other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the conflict in the Middle East and abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany has first of all important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to offend public opinion, but also the elites of Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a determining factor.
However, I would not give it too much importance, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in German strategic reflections.
Does Germany interfere with its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think the Europeans and the Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think that the divide is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, the views on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot of course defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great that they always seem to be so.
If you observe relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu’s policy.
Does Germany have difficulty in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I think it doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore register within a broader political line and must assert their singular position.
This is what they are currently doing in the issue of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will assume a locomotive role in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been tricky.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware that they must play a role that further marks their independence.
Is Germany playing a strong role on the international stage, does Germany only want to take a key role?
Or does it still have difficulty taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still has difficulty playing a greater role.
If we look, for example, at the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German sentiments are heard.
It doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: you do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
She has to deal with very varied neighbors and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only diminishing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this void, so who is left?
