‘Brand Protection’ in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection as the company bearing the name of the mark cannot file a complaint.
And even if she could, it's not certain that she would win the case.
“It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer with Taylor Wessing, a property infringement in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators only need a few more letters to be able to register their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copying, such as Puma, the sports goods manufacturer.
Pattloch opens a workbook in which the registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office are located.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the trademark Zegna DF Puma, a name that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become world champions of copying and infringement of intellectual property.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell almost only counterfeits.
Pattloch's cases, however, are different: his constituents instruct him to address the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially confers on Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese talk about "Bang Mingpai", a parent brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan."
It is with this term that women who marry rich men are referred to.
Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame.
"It's bad for business, we have to fight this trend," says Pattloch.
"The brand is watered down, the singularity disappears, the damage to the reputation is enormous."
Financial losses and legal costs are in the millions for the sectors concerned, especially with regard to expensive flagship products.
According to data from the market analyst CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of 15 billion euros, the third largest global luxury market and the fastest growing market.
However, it is not easy to write down the questionable records from the trademark register and these procedures are expensive.
The latter can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch reports the trials in which the court dismissed the complaint, because after a long period of time, the name criticized had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is not lucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarism, because he would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also involve graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against construction machine builder Sany, the same company that had just bought the concrete pump producer Putzmeister.
That's why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, the Volvo acquirer, used before a blue and white logo that recalled that of BMW. The conflict was settled and Geely had to change it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost to the plagiarists of Hong Kong and Singapore who had reoriented the look of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
However, the CTMO trademark office in Beijing admits to having experienced some difficulties in 2010 because of a lack of staff and space.
However, the office would have gone from an "emergency situation in the course of work to a restored normal" last year.
Thus, the number of untreated opposition proceedings would have fallen by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases would have been closed, which represents an increase of 75% compared to the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 proceedings remain outstanding at the Office.
Acting is expensive
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the OCT received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and that means that China is at the top for the tenth consecutive time for the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal brands, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the office reportedly recorded 1.8 billion yuan of registration fee.
In other words, each record reported an average of 1.280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as illustrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting against a Chinese plagiarism.
Certainly, the Germans were able to obtain that the illegal manufacture of vehicle components be suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain his Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“It’s our fault, because surnames cannot be protected in Germany,” said Hanno Wentzler, chairman of the management of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The trade mark office had therefore rejected the objection of the Munichers.
Freudenberg has certainly won the case in the two subsequent instances, but the opposing side continues to fight until today.
Vigilance is required
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and praises the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: "the procedure is long, challenging and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to assess internal costs. The archives department even had to review the deeds of the last hundred years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg had even proposed in vain to the opposing party a "big sum in six-figure euros" to settle the dispute.
“That’s what we see what it means to us,” Wentzler said.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to spill over to Europe.
This would be the case if imitators from this region were to ensure the exploitation of unprotected trademarks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to lay in Germany the name Freudenberg for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but it could still have prevented the deposit.
Wentzler adds: "Vigilance is required."
Pattloch and his advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, according to them, to rely on international trademark law, foreigners should instead "also register in China everything that is likely to be protected", as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs may be much higher than those of the registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of his legal drama, the company would have to pay license fees to the opposing party for the use of his own name, as Wentzler explains.
Or we would lose our place in the segment of the market in question.
