Many points are therefore subject to interpretation in the draft that Morsi submits to the vote and which, in his own words, will be "very soon" the subject of a referendum with the Egyptians.
"The revolution is reborn"
The opposition has been mobilizing for weeks against the numerical superiority of Islamists.
On Friday night, tens of thousands of protesters gathered in an unusual match in Cairo’s Tahrir Square, promising to bring down the Sharia before it came into effect.
“The revolution is reborn and we will win,” said Hamdin Sabbahi, who came third in the presidential elections.
Nobel Peace Prize winner and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El Baradei said the draft constitution is "to be thrown in the trash cans of history".
On Twitter, the instant messaging service, he accused Morsi’s supporters of wanting to foment a “putsch against democracy.”
