A fight for sovereignty over the symbolic Tharir Square, where everything began, would soon have created a situation similar to that of a civil war.
Obviously, that's what Morsi's supporters wanted to avoid.
The Muslim Brotherhood said opponents of the draft Constitution, like its supporters, had spoken out loud and clear.
According to them, it is now time to let the people decide by the ballot box the direction the country must take.
The project of the Islamists will certainly win the majority.
"Human rights are not mentioned once"
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry at this imposed constitutional process that should have extended until February and encompassed all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) had defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were in prison or in court under Mubarak.
He did so not because he shared their conception of the world, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
That's why he was beaten, tried and imprisoned.
“And now the term is not even pronounced once in the new Constitution,” he said during his meeting with the Welt am Sonntag.
The extension of Morsi's powers to the three powers discouraged the lawyer.
These measures are a glaring attack on the rules of democracy and will generate a new dictatorship in Egypt.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, the president de facto strips him of all his powers," Saeda said.
Yet a democracy cannot work without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels neglected, including by the international community, who look at the battle between the different political ideologies on the edge of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and nervousness.
That could pay for.
A protester in Tharir Square warns, "You give birth to a monster that you will no longer be able to control."
Norway's rakfisk: Is it the world's most fragrant fish?
The five million people in Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country's success be linked to the appetite of the locals for an extremely fragrant fish?
Get some advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a stack of wet and dirty football clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway’s most popular dishes.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It snows, the landscape is spectacular - and this smell, omnipresent, permeates the air.
Rakfisk consists of salt-sprinkled trout and fermented in water for a period of time - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can go up to a year.
When the darkness settles down and it is cold, the Norwegians gather en masse to attend a festival that takes place here in Fagernes, dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
“You eat raw, then you swallow a glass of aquavit,” says Havard Halvarsen, a full-time local firefighter who is also known as “Rakfisk General,” head of festival management.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of drink.
“Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk,” Havard adds.
The drink kills the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you can avoid passing it under your nose, it’s not bad – it’s reminiscent of a sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
Rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, the fish was immersed in airtight water barrels, and then salted in the autumn.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish came out and - without a doubt with the senses diminished by alcohol - eaten.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, emigrating mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted to full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so long ago richer than Norway, cross the border to come to work.
Rakfisk is considered to be something important, a vital, though fragrant, element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a little pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you € 10 each.
Norway does not often make its word on in international news, which is not to displease it.
Here, people are not willing to talk about Anders Breivik, the right-wing extremist racist who shot 77 people, including women and children.
When they mention this killing, they talk about the "incident of July 22".
Norwegians find it difficult to accept that in their peaceful country, one of their own may have committed such an act of barbarism.
Since the early 1970’s, Norway has owed its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
"But oil is not the only reason that justifies our success," says Anna, our waitress, with blonde hair and the eyes of a piercing blue, the image of Nordic well-being, with a tray of rakfisk in hand.
We are - how do you say - cautious people.
His English, like that of most of the people who live here, is perfect.
We are discreet, we do not like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution - all, with the exception of a small percentage of money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries threw money out of the windows, in the years that led us to the international financial crisis, Norway was able to keep the strings of its purse tight.
"As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in the summer, we are happy," says Anna.
“Not to mention the rakfisk,” she added in a carefree laugh.
I stand under the snow and queue to buy myself something to eat - I got my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a burger composed of momentum, a real discovery, it's excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I stay in is one of the many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where you can vote for the best of them - or perhaps for the most fragrant of them.
There is a TV show where the presenter wears a butterfly knot, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It's like the Eurovision contest.
"What score did you give to the best fish in the Thor-Juergen Mountains?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
You can hear laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps because of the abuse of aquavit.
Or maybe it's because of the fish emanations.
The Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto is having a difficult start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, Will Grant of the BBC is interested in the difficulties that await him and the expectations of the people, which are numerous.
Road traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where traffic jams are legion in normal times, a security checkpoint has been set up since Monday, blocking several key road accesses in the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
Nevertheless, the goal was not to prevent people from getting to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
Next Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential scarf to become the new president at the head of the nation.
A complicated task awaits him.
Mexico's economy is doing well, from the results we owe to outgoing President Felipe Calderon, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already claimed the lives of about 60,000 people in six years.
“My government has made a commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Mr. said. Pena Nieto to U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before rubbing shoulders with the US President, Mr. Pena Nieto was governor of the state of Mexico.
A very populated and sprawling state that encloses the capital. On his favorite land, opinions about this new leader are divided.
A direct man
In the bucolic commune of Valle del Bravo, for example, it is inscribed in the memory of all.
The premises attribute to him the development of tourism and infrastructure in the municipality.
To reach the city, you can take one of the new highways of M Pena Nieto, a significant improvement has been made to these roads, once bumpy and full of crevices.
Plaques bearing his name hang outside a new sports complex and an impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We are counting on him to implement lasting change,” said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a member of the congress and party of Mr. Pena Nieto, the PRI.
In terms of security and economy in particular, we hope for a real change that our country so badly needs.
After 81 unfailing years in power, the PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, there are many expectations within the party concerning Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects the criticism of opponents who blame the new president for lack of charisma.
He is a whole, very committed man, with an excellent vision of the country.
He is an excellent statesman and, above all, he knows how to listen.
However, this is not always the image of the people of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be more glaring.
Hidden under the highways, it is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City.
And the problems in the municipality are also concrete and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called to the rescue to fight against the drug gangs in the neighbourhoods, and violence against women is particularly serious.
In a disaster area, the bodies of dozens of women murdered over the past two years have been found on the edge of the landfill.
More than 1,000 women were killed in the state of Mexico while Mr. Pena Nieto was governor, a much higher rate than in the very violent city of Ciudad Juarez - a place infamous for the number of innocent women who were killed there.
The critics of M. Pena Nieto, say that at best, he failed to stem the problem of murders perpetrated against women when he was in office.
At worst, they accuse his administration of refusing to see reality in the face.
In a concrete house, typical of this dilapidated neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles to hold back her tears when she shows me photos of her late daughter, Mariana Luna.
The official version mentions a suicide committed by Mariana in 2010.
However, her family thinks she was killed by her partner.
"When I arrived home, it seemed to me that her body had been washed," says the Señora Buendia.
Signs indicated that she had been beaten, and the cadaveric rigidity was already underway.
While her mother tells the story, a photo of Mariana dresses the wall, next to a cross where the word is featured: Justice.
However, this is exactly what the family was denied.
The authorities treated me like I was an old gossip, a troubled crab, a whining woman.
They want us to accept what they say and shut up.
“But it’s not normal that there are so many irregularities and omissions,” she said.
When President Pena Nieto receives her scarf on Saturday, she will be accompanied by a heavy responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by crime in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has made a promise that he will make it his priority during his term.
“I hope he will be as good as he was as president as he was when he was governor,” Olvera told Congressman Valle del Bravo.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter the claims of abuse that Bradley Manning was allegedly subjected to during the detention.
The trial is about Manning's detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence wants to close the case on the grounds that Manning's kidnapping was in extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to demonstrate Friday that Private Bradley Manning — accused of being behind the biggest leak of confidential information in the history of the U.S. military — has missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein claimed that records of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine months in detention at Quantico, Virginia, did not reveal any complaints about his treatment.
Cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a motion requiring that the Manning case be closed on the basis that the kidnapping was in very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place a day after Manning testified to his desire to commit suicide while in detention.
The military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday's hearing, Fein discussed with Manning the forms that the officers had completed after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in the military prison in Quantico, where he was subjected to maximum prison solitary confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein mentioned the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment of his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he had had in the prison was generally "very professional."
The forms do not include any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning responded that he had orally expressed concerns about some of the issues and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would address them, but they did not document the issues raised.
“They wrote ‘no problem’ (after addressing the concerns), and yet, that didn’t mean I didn’t raise any issues,” Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment in a January 2011 interview with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to change his restrictive status indicating a "risk of injury".
The military said they assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was okay, and I wanted to be removed from this status... in order to enjoy a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he considered committing suicide while in Kuwait and fainted once because of the heat.
He added that the fact that he was not kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once at Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell — at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours — without a company.
Manning also added that the only objects he had were a mattress, blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to stay in motion, because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also said that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards didn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning's January 2011 treatment.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony on Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked overnight in his cell at Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other detainees one morning, during the call.
Manning testified that at no time was it allowed him to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he had inferred from the order of his guard that he had to let go of his cover that could have hidden his nakedness, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to let go.
Manning testified Thursday that he was forced to sleep naked the night before, as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his briefs or flip-flops to hurt himself, but that he had not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will consider the experiences he had during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he were to be convicted in court martial, a trial that is expected to be held early next year.
The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty to the least serious offenses and fight for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors arguing that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning has been incarcerated in accordance with the regulations that govern the conditions of detention of all detainees at Quantico.
Charges against Manning include the theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, giving rise to the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of national defence information.
If all charges are held, he is liable to life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He says many have been forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame those who have left; they remind Mexicans of difficult times, he said.
Navarrette says that the Mexico-Americans find themselves caught between two worlds.
During a recent trip to Mexico City, arriving in the lobby, in front of the customs and immigration services, I felt lost.
Signs indicated two lanes: one for the "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for the "Extranjeros" ("Overthen").
I stood still for several seconds, not knowing which line to point me.
I grew up in central California, where I've been called the "Mexican" my whole life.
This is an ethnic qualifier, just like the one my friends in Boston use when they call themselves "Irish," or my friends in New York when they call themselves "Italian."
Then I became "Mexico-American."
But here it was Mexico.
And, on the earth that saw my grandfather born, no need for a special qualifier or a hyphen.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, good enough to handle an interview in either language.
But I don't have the vocabulary of an indigenous, and I can't lose my American accent.
So I took my American passport and headed to the "Foreign" line.
I thought about that time of the week when the new Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited President Obama at the White House.
Generally, when the leaders of these two countries meet, their favorite themes are immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto also wanted to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one of the reasons why Mexicans stay in Mexico rather than risking themselves in the United States.
He wants to join forces with the United States and Canada, and create a Union for Trade on the model of the European Union, but in North America.
And Pena Nieto pledges to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, although he has not provided further details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and filled with bitterness.
Most Americans probably never thought about the fact that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give in writing half of their territory at the tip of the rifle.
But for Mexicans, who think in terms of centuries, and no minutes, memories are everywhere.
Therefore, as soon as a U.S. official makes any criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear - in the Mexican press, and among the elites -- complaints about how the Americans are undermining the sovereignty of their neighbor.
And the children of Montezuma are looking for a fight.
And yet, for Mexico, the most difficult relationship is the one the country has with the more than 35 million Mexico-Americans living in the United States.
You want us to address the subject of bitterness?
There are many.
Mexico has its winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities and others for whom the country does not offer them.
The only reason why the large number of Mexican ancestors in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, is that at one point, in our family tree, a person, maybe a parent or grandparent, found no opportunity in Mexico and had to go north.
And more often than not, this person corresponded to a typical profile -- a dark, poorly educated skin, from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants, and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And even though we are currently living the American dream, that we have gone to good schools and we have good situations, we must never lose sight of the fact that this is the American dream we are living, not that of Mexicans.
Our identity is sometimes disturbed, but our loyalty is obvious.
We give it to the United States.
On the other hand, we know that a part of the Mexican elite among the ruling class does not love us.
The feeling is reciprocal.
We remind them of a humiliating defeat and they limp us as if we were individuals of inferior strain and not enough Mexican.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
For them, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed when they lived in Mexico, they would never have left.
And we wouldn't find ourselves stuck on the right side of the fence, living comfortably in the United States, but like lost souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and who emigrated legally to the United States while she was a child, reminds me that there are frictions between Mexicans and Mexico-Americans, because Mexicans are more firmly claiming their identity and Mexico-Americans are upset about it.
Although she is a U.S. citizen, she feels she is a member of two countries.
On the other hand, many Mexico-Americans I know do not feel like they are part of one country or another.
We love the music of the Mexican band, Los Tigres del Norte, but also that of Bruce Springsteen.
We have the best of both worlds, but we are not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we are considered Americans.
And in the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
And now, to complicate the relationship a little more, as I learned during my stay, some Mexican leaders and part of the intelligentsia want to get closer to the Diaspora.
They want Mexico-Americans to work as makeshift ambassadors for Mexico, representing his interests in the United States.
We will have to explain to our fellow Americans that Mexico is a superb country that must absolutely be visited and put pressure on political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course.
That won't happen.
There's too much bitterness.
And, considering the wage inequality, corruption and drug-related violence that are pervasive, many of us are not convinced that this is a fantastic country.
You're gonna have to manage on your own, amigos.
That's normal.
If some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, they must therefore accept that some Mexico-Americans still want them the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old quarrels, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas is still a failure for peace.
Can there never be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed seems to indicate that such hope is in vain.
While the same futile arguments for who began, dozens of buildings were reduced to dust; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them were civilians, and six Israelis were killed; and, for the first time, rockets fired from Gaza landed near Tel Aviv, the metropolis of Israel, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But although the Israelis and Palestinians seem stuck in their old conflict, all around them, the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has made everything shatter, and whether we like it or not, the Palestinians and the Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
Maybe their struggle will intensify a little more.
Yet there is every reason to think that it could help them out of this deadly impasse.
A war that makes no losers or winners
At first glance, it seems difficult to be optimistic.
Even though the ceasefire granted on November 21 is continuing, this week’s fighting has strengthened the force’s supporters on both sides.
Hamas leaders, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will pride themselves on forcing the Israelis to abandon, even though Gaza has suffered a beating.
Killing some of its leaders and repressing Gaza’s 1.7 million people in one of the most miserable and overcrowded corners of the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground on the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently in the hands of their Fatah rivals, the other more moderate Palestinian faction.
Moreover, the leaders of Hamas could say that time is their ally.
The influence of the Islamists in the Arab world is growing stronger, and Hamas has made rich and powerful friends.
Turkey, a booming regional power, once Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken up the cause for Hamas; just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Hamas operatives are glowing and say that the growing Islamist is bending around Israel, from Lebanon, in the north, where the Hezbollah militia is exercising its domination, through Syria, where Islamist-tensive rebels can overthrow Bashar Al-Assad, and to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And the most important, on the southern flank of Israel, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under the presidency of Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and central of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time to devote to Hamas.
On the other hand, the Muslim Brotherhood is cousins of Hamas, and their leaders rely more easily on public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas can emerge as an important actor who can no longer be excluded even by Israel and America.
Meanwhile, supporters of Israel’s hard line will draw the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas has been rebounded.
The missile interception system called Iron Dome proved its effectiveness and many Hamas missiles were destroyed.
The Israelis will be able to sleep in both their ears - for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, America renews its unwavering support; and many European countries have criticized Hamas for being at the origin of the latest wave of violence.
But above all, Israel has prospered, especially under Binyamin Netanyahu, the prime minister, who has totally ignored the peace process.
Although the firing of rockets from Gaza has killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been spared suicide bombings, including through the separation barrier that encroaches on the West Bank, the main piece of what could be a Palestinian state, and that protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite their illegality under international law.
M. Netanyahu, whose Likud party has merged with an even more warmongering party, that of leader Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 election, has the beautiful part.
Why pamper these damn Palestinians by giving them a state?
If they were running the West Bank, would they not launch rockets, as their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is best to keep them behind this wall and hit them as soon as they come out their heads.
Perhaps the hard-lined supporters will prevail; but the Arab Spring may be a game changer.
Even if Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere do not appreciate Israel, their priority will be to tackle the problems in their own countries.
Israel's defense budget is more important than that of its four Arab neighbors together.
Starting a war with the local superpower will not help the new Arab governments to arrange their economies.
M. Morsi worked with Barack Obama to get a ceasefire which bodes well -- and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis should also think about the future.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination could create a powder keg that is destined to explode one day in the territories occupied by Israel – much like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already weakening democracy in the Jewish state, and demographics are exacerbating this problem as the Arab population grows.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to sound Hamas will have a diplomatic price.
Both sides need to be pushed by those from the outside.
The answer remains that advocated by the reasonable people found on either side, and by most of the outside world and by this newspaper: two states, with a surrender of territory by Israel in exchange for security.
A hope, small and short-term, is that the ceasefire will provide an opportunity for outsiders to defend this cause.
Egypt, which must now address the end of the flow of weapons to Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is better placed than ever to persuade Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state in accordance with the 1967 borders with exchanges of land and a shared Jerusalem.
Arabs from outside countries should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to unite.
This would contribute much more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming proposal of a pseudo-state to the United Nations.
M. Obama also has every interest in Israel agreeing to negotiate.
During his first term, he did not present his own peace plan.
Back at the White House, he seems just as reluctant to establish one.
It's a very narrow vision.
The stability of the Middle East is a vital issue for America.
This is a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
The laws for neutral cigarette packs have come into effect in Australia
Warnings and photos of sick organs cover dark green packages that are all identical, regardless of the brand
This law that came into effect in Australia is a world first, logos and colors have been replaced by a dark olive green and horrible photos of sick organs and depictions of children and babies whose diseases have been caused by the smoking of their parents.
Apart from the various photos and health warnings, the only difference between the packages, since this Saturday, is the name of the brand, printed in small print on all packages.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government has said the goal is to deter young people from smoking by removing any glamorous representations.
Studies have shown that if people have not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that they will never start.
“Even when they’re very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobaccomakers through their brand image,” federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek said, citing studies that revealed, for example, that children were pairing the crown with a logo with a princess.
Even though Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are considering a similar approach.
The tobacco industry has lobbied against this law.
Tobacco manufacturers have said this will boost the black market trade, which will make it easier to access cheaper cigarettes.
“Pedicable consequences will arise from this legislation,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
The counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will sell far more counterfeit cigarettes on the streets of Australia.
Others said the law had boosted their activity.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said the demand for cigarette cases, including silicone cases to mask horrible packaging, has risen sharply two months ago since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco challenged the law and lost to Australia's high court.
Ha said that Zico has sold 6,000 to wholesalers and is waiting for stock renewal.
For us, business is good.
The only trouble, experts say, is the popularity of social media and the segment of the population targeted by the plan.
