For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living carrying the sulfur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gas emanating from the bowels of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After harvesting large sulfur rocks, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep trails.
There are only 250 meters up to the summit of the volcano which rises to 2.386 meters above sea level, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle-like appearance, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to trip and fall into the precipice.
They know that a misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilo of sulfur extracted.
Once at the top, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and painfully carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the balance that a mining company has installed a little below at 1.850 meters of altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has operated the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) per kilo of sulfur.
It then sells it to 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even serves to whiten sugar.
“As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) with each trip,” says Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Everyone takes him 3 hours and he finishes exhausted, but it allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is the triple of what he would gain in the fields.
“The income of miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” says the porter who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) a day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto came back near his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java so that she could be converted"
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life defying danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulfur has already started to charge him the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
