That's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Struggled by life, this friendly and intelligent young could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but, instead, he does the work of a mule.
It shares a masure of unsanitary wood with other wearers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulfur does not cease to spring up at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater lighting up with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers charge the baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own and are paid by weight.
In addition, they also do not receive a sun of the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) of surcharge per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is done for animals, not for humans,” said Madrusin, a 42-year-old body-wizer who has been working in Kawah Ijen for thirty years, since he left college.
Capable of carrying up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18 years.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which are obviously added their usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and shoulders, distorted by the weight of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on his back, Unainik, 53, can only charge 50 kilos.
Every day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away by a goat trail overrun by weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life," Unainik said, opening my mouth, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, aged 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult professions in the world: that made by the human mules of the volcano Kawah ljen.
Singapore looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame this lack of children on the career, stress and cost of homeownership.
"The people of Singapore need to develop."
I am a husband and patriot, you are my wife and a patriot, let us fulfill our civic duty and give life!
It may seem unlikely that these lyrics come from an advertisement for mint lozenges, but despite this, or perhaps thanks to that, the video spread like wildfire on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references like "Let's go put a polichinelle in the drawer" to make fun of Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency behind the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way through this advertising.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music to make people fulfill “their national duty.”
It is intended only for the Internet, so we were able to make it entertaining and fun.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the field of birth rate, so we felt that this was a theme that we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried several things like throwing perfumes at pheromones or organizing speed-dating parties.
Many of these ideas were creative but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we said the following thing: what could be more creative to solve this problem than to make it a rap song?
1.2 children
The Singapore government doesn’t take it so lightly.
It spends US$1,300 a year on policies to encourage its citizens to have more children.
A government measure in favour of marriages and fathers grants up to US$15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, in line with its national population distribution, is currently at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered the renewal rate, was in 1976.
Why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policies for the National Population Division, says it is due to a "better education" and "a wider choice of career opportunities."
“This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and family building,” she says.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in the number of singles and to delay marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter the decline in the population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound a barely disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially against Chinese people who are accused of pulling wages down and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the party in place in Singapore last year experienced its worst electoral results since independence.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a country’s economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore’s example also has unintended consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, it started to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as the "shoebox", which can be built in specific areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, the authorities are concerned that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, managing director of real estate firm EL Developers, says his "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these housings are built much faster than those of larger size.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to developers, who were previously put in the wheels if they wanted to offer too many small dwellings in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If these new regulations can be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by talking with Singaporeans working in the financial district of the centre, it would seem that they will not have much effect.
“People are very stressed, homes are expensive, just like education, that’s why people put it off,” says a young executive.
Other people can have children.
"But for me, it's important to have my money and time," said another young man in our 20s.
Men and women mention their careers, the stress and cost of access to property and education as the reasons for having children.
So, although the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, it is the Singaporeans themselves who have the last word.
What is private offline is private online
Confidentiality
In accordance with the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, this is the quality of the private domain or "the domain of privacy that we can protect from any intrusion".
What is in the private domain for those under 16?
How to apply this definition in everyday life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he exposes himself to by broadcasting events on the Internet that he would certainly not share offline?
The newspaper elPeriódico interviewed five young boys, aged between 10 and 15, frequent users of the web.
In four cases, they associated the term "something very personal" on a personal level and "the password and username" when they applied it to social networks.
“I won’t reveal my most personal secrets in a post,” says Jorge, ten, when he tries to explain the meaning of the private term on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had an account for two years.
