On FB, I post nice pictures or games.
I also talk to my friends.
“I won’t share one of my photos or someone who would be the fool,” he said.
The young boy acknowledges that it is wrong to post obscene photos, naked people, crimes or write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge says he knows his 35 friends on FB as well as his nine followers on Twitter.
The majority are family.
Her mother is one of them, she knows the password of one of the accounts.
I opened a Twitter account to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if they answer me, I just post them,” he added.
“Social media is fun, I can talk with distant relatives or with my friends, quickly,” he says.
He says he would never accept the request of an unknown person.
He will not trust anyone who would recommend a stranger to him either.
The case of José, 14, is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter, he admits not to know 20 of the people registered on his list of friends.
“I’m not worried because we have something in common, music for example,” he said.
According to the boy, no one made advances to him or asked for his address or phone number.
“If they put pressure on me or demanded it, I would simply delete them from my account,” he admits.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences we know today as cyberbullying are no stranger to the young boy.
A relative of a friend of mine was racketed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
“He never knew who he was,” he said.
The victim, according to José, did not close his account.
"He only passed it in a private profile."
He then explains a series of manipulations to configure his account in a safe way.
Unlike Jorge, this young person would post photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I'd do it if I was angry or angry.
“Even though I know it’s cyberbullying,” he said.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, English teacher and graduate in Education and Learning, considers that, in order to guide children and adolescents, it must be understood that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
“The Internet has emerged as a way to look for information but, with the appearance of these sites, the rule of the game has changed,” she said.
Porras reports that academician Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in pedagogy from Yale University and author of the book "Natives and Digital Immigrants", uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are the children and young people who were born with technology.
“We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them there, while we ourselves are learning,” she says.
He adds that the theme is complex, "because we ask them to have a defined criterion on what should or should not be disclosed, published or said at an age when they do not have the maturity to do so."
“We also ask them to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,” she added.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach privacy to children and adolescents is to use questions that make them think.
“Teaching them not to do it is useless,” she said.
Then, Porras lists a few examples: there are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like them to post a picture of you like that of a friend you published?
Do you know what others post about you?
When you identify holiday photos, do you ask other people for permission to identify them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you are doing every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they must act online as they do offline.
These are the same rules.
“Outside the Internet, everyone has to act with respect, morality and other principles, it has to be the same on social media,” she said.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and education counselor, says it is essential that parents conscientiously read the conditions of use of social networks.
By understanding each of the terms, they will have a solid foundation for discussing with their children the implications of opening an account on the Internet.
“For example, age and what is allowed to share or publish,” he says.
According to Guardia, it is essential to remind children that we should not talk to foreigners.
The Unasur summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration having been made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Unasur Heads of State and Government, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the summit closed, and then claimed that it would be published from one time to the next on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its content had been exposed by Peru's President Ollante Humala in brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The lack of information circulating between the journalists was that given by the press attachés of some of the Unasur governments who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document leaked during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who were demanding more important information.
Later, Peru’s presidency sent an email to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but it was President Humala’s speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South America-Arab Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although this was requested with a forum by the press, it had also not circulated the statement also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to set up safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they have limited the availability of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court which decides a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleas of both sides in the lawsuit that Lima filed against Santiago and begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we face today before this international court,” said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of international controversies, treaties and tribunals,” Piñera said, giving a handshake to President Humala, alongside the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia this week denounced the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that international tribunal, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua, which it considered to be gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the impeachment of its ex-president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total of 17 million dollars of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of Unasur would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better accessibility to medicines, low-cost Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "the economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to see a better future for our populations," concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to focus on a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the cross-cutting axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aiming for a larger connection with Ecuador although it did not give further details.
Similarly, the outcome document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
Another theme addressed at the summit is the need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations with its neighbours.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through an ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
“It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega,” Santos said.
"We will revise all these paths, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua which will ask to have a discussion with this country," he said.
“I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,” Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City where they have planned to attend the seizure of power of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, within the framework of the summit, the Bloc’s defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
“South America needs to learn from Europe how to integrate a citizenship,” says Rafael Correa.
Ecuador’s President Rafael Correa said today that the creation of a common citizenship was a goal for which “South America, in this case, must take example of Europe.”
President Correa, who participated in the VI summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, told state television, TV Peru, that Europeans "had killed themselves during the Second World War" and in other conflicts, "but that they were now almost a homeland".
In this sense, he defended the plan to establish a South American citizenship encouraged by the member countries of Unasur.
"We must achieve the free movement of citizens and workers in any South American country, as is already the case for the members of the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary areas that we want to make belong to the past," he warned.
In addition, the President of Ecuador has shown himself in favour of the reconstitution of the Organization of American States (OAS) with the objective of diminishing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states and taking into account the signatories of the San José Pact on Human Rights.
Those who reshuffle our ears never compromise anything, conversely, we South Americans have all signed it.
“It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is in Washington under the funding of the United States,” he said, referring to the political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa assures that he does not regret his decision, because he himself has not betrayed his principles, but on the contrary he has respected his "deep democratic values and human rights".
He concluded that at the time, “there were well-founded suspicions that Assange would be extradited to a third country and that his trial would not be respected.”
In addition, he criticizes the Swedish court, which has demanded that he submit to his territory for interrogation of an alleged sexual offence while "the Swedish legislation allows it to be done by videoconference, which could be done from the Ecuadorian embassy in London".
Correa stated that there is a risk that Assange's mental and physical health will deteriorate.
"I have not spoken to him since he is in our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he had a small lung problem, but nothing serious," he said.
It is possible that his physical and mental health will deteriorate by being locked in a small space without being able to do outdoor exercises.
“This affects the health of anyone,” he concludes.
Correa reports that the asylum solution granted to Assange since June in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, which would be the allocation of a safe-conduct that would allow him to travel to Ecuador, is in the hands of Britain, Sweden and European judicial authorities and he points out that he has had discussions in London in order to find a solution to the confinement of the WikiLeaks founder.
We do not negotiate with human rights, we do not use that word in this case, but there have been ongoing discussions.
"The solution to this problem is in the hands of Britain, Sweden and the European judicial authorities because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, has launched a whole series of proceedings with various European bodies," he said.
And he thinks that "if Britain granted the safe-conduct tomorrow, it would end."
And if Sweden, as its legislation allows altogether, and as it has already done in other cases, would question Mr. Assange in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, or interrogated him via Skype tomorrow, the problem would also be solved.
Correa took the opportunity to reaffirm himself as a defender of press freedom and he said that what he did not tolerate was "mediocrity, bad faith and lies that undermine freedom of expression".
“The biggest enemies of press freedom are not malicious or perverse politicians but bad journalists in the pay of greed, blackmail and extortion,” he said.
From this angle, he welcomed that this is not the kind of journalists "neither the bankers nor the hegemonic and bourgeois countries that dominate in Ecuador" and, rather than highlighting his re-election, "he would deepen the revolution to continue the path and chart the right path".
Correa also supported the decision to keep the veto on Paraguay within Unasur at least until the next elections, arguing that the organization "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and attempted coup d'état in disguise", because in reality, "it destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy."
Moreover, the Ecuadorian president considers as "perfectly relevant" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court of The Hague, which will strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
At the moment, this judgment is not respected.
This is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overwhelmed by the will to move forward together.
We have to solve them as a whole to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he said he was confident in the good resolution of the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile in the same tribunal and said it is "beneficial that Latin America should refer international bodies to the two countries if they agree to accept a judgment so firm as it is".
Referring to the possibility of his presentation as a candidate in the future presidential elections in Ecuador, with a view to running for a third consecutive term, he reported that he saw this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although it is sometimes quite difficult".
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 primaries, he would withdraw from public life.
At the personal level, power has never interested me, but in situations as unfair as those of Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be resolved through political power.
"My political movement believed that it was I who guaranteed this eventual victory but we must accept this responsibility," he said.
If I won, it would be my last presidential term and then I will retire from political life.
If we ever lose, I will do it too.
“That’s my decision,” he said.
Correa also referred to the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
“This does not mean a relapse of President Chávez’s state of health,” he said.
