AIDS-related deaths are now due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed the result of the test: HIV positive.
“It’s like the sky fell on my head,” he said, referring to the time of the announcement, that the doctor had tried to make “less painful,” in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to learn about him and his relentlessness was such that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is, without a doubt, one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit at the Guadalajara Civilian Hospital (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 90s, where there were many doubts, few treatment choices and more stigmas.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless."
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the onset of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory is today that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HCG HIV unit, and he takes as a reference that this information was validated in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectiologist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a fatal disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depended on the level of assignment of the immune system that patients had at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those not using drugs: up to 30 years for a CD4 rate of 200 and up to 50 years
To put it simply, it means that for someone who would receive a positive HIV diagnosis at 25, "as long as he remains under control, will be able to live without problems until the age of 75," the scientist explained.
In order to put this progress in context, it should be noted that the life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years on average.
While mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died from AIDS has increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), but it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of patients on the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths until May of this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
Why are there still deaths?
I think the problem is not access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the past 12 years at least, we have never missed any medication, the problem is that patients arrive at very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or they learn it in advanced stages of the disease.
He gives us an indisputable fact "nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, for this, we must offer screening tests in a massive way, to all the people who ask for it".
Specialists and members of the State AIDS Prevention Council of Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as well as the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to do his screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done so and that, despite his young age, he was already carrying AIDS and was suffering from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know.
"If I'm going to die, it's better that I have fun three times a week," they say, "it's not my case.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
To this day, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, just like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, through his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the World AIDS Day march.
Let them do the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV-positive and the better, and if they already have the diagnosis, they must know that we can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the ordinary citizen, argues Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who embraced the cause of HIV.
The biggest is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packets of one hundred, it is very good, but the result is that even today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections is adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", asked with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, guidance counselors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers do not want to hear, says the journalist.
It proposes to reorient this inefficient distribution; that condoms are not only sold at the counters, but that they are found in public toilet dispensers and in the places that young people frequent.
It is not a matter of encouraging promiscuity.
It is also not a question of paying them the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González had replied when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
“This is not how sexuality works, the best is to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active,” he said.
Numbers to Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12.158 AIDS and 1.317 HIV).
The State is the 4th State of the country in number of new cases and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th for the number of HIV patients.
92% of contamination is sexually, 6% by blood and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for each case recorded, there are 4 or 5 people who do not.
A judgment ratified on appeal by a U.S. court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group’s debt through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico. The scenario raises a harmful precedent for all national societies with ramifications in the neighbouring country with solvency problems.
It seems, therefore, that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the starry banner, against international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the judgment rendered on June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the North District of Texas, leaves Mexican companies defenseless in the face of the possibility of an embargo of their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico’s leading glass manufacturer to refer the case to the U.S. Supreme Court based on three inconsistencies.
First, while the case judge reports that creditors must register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Appeals Court, sitting in New Orleans, claims that the main procedure is formalized commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing the cooperation of international proceedings in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Trade Law had been created for this purpose by taking the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that without the inter-corporate voting, recognised in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts incurred by Vitro's subsidiaries towards the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
