Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Baskelball is my whole life"
Basketball globetrotter “Hetin” Reyes has spent more than 60 years of his life in connection with the field and, thanks to him, has traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as big as that of Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a brain hemorrhage condemned him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, national basketball team player, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or as president of the basketball federation.
"I have worn several caps in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, such as when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 90s," Reyes recalls during a visit to Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he resides with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball is my whole life."
Reyes doesn't exaggerate when he makes that statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that recall his extraordinary itinerary, testify to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he likes the most are those that remind him of his time as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-50s until 1982, after spending 15 years as a co-manager or team manager.
“It was my best years, the best ones I enjoyed the most because I had the chance to compete in eight Vaqueros championships from 1967, whether as a manager, co-manager or manager.
It has been many years of satisfaction, including the five championships played from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired in the championship in 1981, the year that Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team, "says Reyes.
I remember that Gene Bartow, who had been a leader here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), told me: "I have a strong player for you, he measures two meters.
Do you want it?"
That’s how Mincy started, one of the best players Puerto Rico had.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He was delighted with the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his and Mincy's charges in the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the 1989 pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we came 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge hadn’t made us play the last game again,” Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you’ve ever seen?
She is one of the best, as is the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite is the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won the gold and put a beating to the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that won bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 because of a problem
A team that may not have been the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy at the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing the players suspended by the imbroglio of the Pan American Games of Mar del Plata, we won the gold against all predictions.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it is Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics in international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico dominated at this level as Piculín did.
And this without taking into account his trajectory in the different leagues for which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team consisting of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I really like the work that Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest success within the federation?
Having been part of the most glorious time of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s, the BSN had up to 17 teams in a season.
What do you have left to do?
There are things that I would have liked to put in place, such as the regionalization of the minor categories.
For example, that the boys of Ponce play only in their area and only face teams from other corners of the island during national playoffs.
Today, young people travel and play too much while it is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the benefit of mandatory certifications and courses for executives, field staff and referees.
That makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, I watch music videos of my time on YouTube, I enjoy my grandchildren and, from time to time, I attend basketball games.
And of course, I take advantage of the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide by the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played an unscrupulous, formidable and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of avarice in the 1980's, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year in the role of J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a statement from the family sent to The associated Press for Warner Bros., a production company of "Dallas".
“Larry was back in his dear hometown of Dallas, playing again the ironic role he loved the most,” the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife's role in the original series and in the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, his press secretary, Jeffrey Lane, said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him a lot.
“He was an exceptional person and he was living life thoroughly,” Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he had admitted to having drunk a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was detected a malignant liver tumour and had undergone a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made himself known on television in the role of an ordinary guy in the series "Jinny of my dreams" broadcast by the NBC channel from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered an attractive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and that he brought her home.
He also starred in two comedies that remained on the air for a short time, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his film roles are roles well received by critics in "The Band", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the delightfully detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman was his greatest success.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and their relatives aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who killed J.R.?", invented to maintain the suspense around an episode full of emotions in which the character of Hagman is almost murdered, has generated speculation around the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached an audience record at that time.
When the response was revealed in an episode of November 1980, an average of 41 million viewers were in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most-watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot her.
J.R. had pregnant her and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reason to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable but charismaticly smiling man: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who was trying to have his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) interned.
“I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R,” Hagman said in 1988.
One should write: "This is the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
Here's the only part he's lost.
Victoria Principal, co-rotagonist of the original series, recalled this Friday of Hagman as a man "immense, both on the small screen and in life".
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us, who have had the chance to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes is already finished for the second season and a sixth is in the process of directing, the channel has informed.
For the time being, neither Warner nor TNT have communicated about how Hagman’s death will be incorporated into the series.
Originally from Fort Worth, Texas, he is the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who knew fame with classic works like "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Mary Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to her in 1931 when she was married to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He took his first steps on the stages of the New York theaters in the early 1950s and then served in the air force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
It was there that he met the young Swedish interior designer Maj Axelsson and married him.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for many years in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he titled his memoirs "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life": Hello Darlin': The Merciless Memoirs of J.R.
“I didn’t write anything in this book that could hurt someone or affect them in any way,” he told reporters at the time.
After his liver transplant, he became an active organ donation activist and worked as a volunteer in a hospital to assist worried patients.
"I advise them, I give them confidence, I come with them when they come to have surgery and after," he said in 1996.
I try to offer them some comfort, like "Don't be afraid, it won't be easy for a little while, but it's going to be okay."
He has also been a tobacco activist and has participated in several campaigns.
A course on the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was throwing an irresistible hook there: the end of the "great count" of the Mayan calendar, on December 21, to which many people refer to as being the proof of the imminent end of the world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what to expect in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a fiscal chasm that some have dubbed the “Debt Armageddon” and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where end-time Christian theorists thought the apocalypse would be triggered.
“I didn’t realize that this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I’ve ever known,” Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And we must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he is not the only professor to give courses on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply titled "The End of the World."
“We’re adding ‘2012’ to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world doesn’t disappear,” Professor Restall said.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and take their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed the day before the Apocalypse, leaving students with no choice but to work “until the very night of the supposed end of the world,” Restall said.
Classes have proved to be quite popular.
“It’s been full in two hours,” Restall said of its course for high-level students, consisting of 35 students.
We received email messages several weeks before the start of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves,” says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old religious and sociology student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, University of Rutgers-Camden.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or of lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and infirmary student, says he has watched all the apocalyptic films.
“I had never heard of a course teaching this subject,” he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone a professor, told us to believe in the end date of the world of December 21.
“Our first project dealt with Mayan prophecy, and in a way we discredited it,” said Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old graduate student at Temple from West Chester.
The Mayans have never predicted the end of the world, it’s only a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I concede that there is anxiety related to the apocalypse in Western culture, dating back centuries, which makes people react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a rise in these speculations.
“In other parts of the world, people don’t think about that,” he said.
This is the majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a religious professor at La Salle University who lectures in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew he was given classes here on "the end of the world."
“The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world,” he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall points out that over the years, we have talked about the many supposed dates of the last judgment, and he says that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing about the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a 7-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and professors take the date lightly.
Several told us that they thought they were going to “the end of the world” parties.
“Sometimes I call friends and we laugh about it together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
